<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Is pregnancy massage safe?</h3>

<p>
For most women with an uncomplicated pregnancy, pregnancy massage is considered safe when provided by a healthcare professional trained in pregnancy care. Before every appointment, we discuss your medical history, stage of pregnancy and any concerns to ensure treatment is appropriate for you. Side-lying positioning is commonly used to maximise comfort and safety during treatment. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
</p>

<h3>When can I have a postnatal massage?</h3>

<p>
Many women benefit from postnatal massage once they feel comfortable after childbirth. The most appropriate timing depends on your recovery, whether you had a vaginal birth or Caesarean section, and any advice from your healthcare team. Treatment is always tailored to your stage of recovery.
</p>

<h3>Can massage help pregnancy-related back pain?</h3>

<p>
Massage therapy may help reduce muscle tension, improve comfort and promote relaxation. When combined with physiotherapy assessment, exercise and education, it can form part of an effective treatment plan for pregnancy-related musculoskeletal pain. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
</p>

<h3>Do I need a GP referral?</h3>

<p>
No. You can book directly with SU Women's Health Physiotherapy & Wellness Clinic without a GP referral.
</p>

<h3>Can massage be combined with physiotherapy?</h3>

<p>
Absolutely. Massage therapy often works best as part of a wider rehabilitation programme that may include physiotherapy assessment, manual therapy, exercise prescription, posture advice and self-management strategies. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}
</p>

<h3>How many sessions will I need?</h3>

<p>
Some women experience significant improvement after one session, while others benefit from a short course of treatment. Your physiotherapist will discuss an individual treatment plan based on your symptoms, goals and progress.
</p>

<h3>What should I wear?</h3>

<p>
Wear comfortable clothing. We will explain exactly what to expect before treatment begins, and your privacy and comfort will always be respected.
</p>

<h3>Can I have massage after a Caesarean section?</h3>

<p>
Yes. Once it is clinically appropriate, massage can help relieve muscular tension associated with caring for your baby. If your Caesarean scar requires specific rehabilitation, we can also advise on scar management and appropriate physiotherapy.
</p>

